---

<Base
  title="Bona Fide Marriage Letter 2026: How to Write One + Sample Template"
  description="How to write a bona fide relationship letter for immigration — what to include, what to avoid, full sample template, and tips for K-1, CR-1, and IR-1 applications."
  schema={schema}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="breadcrumb-bar" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="container">
      <ol class="breadcrumb">
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
        <li><SmartLink href="/bona-fide-marriage">Bona Fide Marriage</SmartLink></li>
        <li aria-current="page">Relationship Letter</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-badge">✉️ Writing Guide</div>
      <h1>Bona Fide Marriage Letter<br/><span>How to Write One That Works</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">A strong personal statement can be the difference between a confident approval and a lengthy RFE. Here's exactly what to write, what to skip, and a full sample template for K-1 and CR-1 applications.</p>
      <div class="letter-summary-bar">
        <div class="lsb-item">
          <span class="lsb-label">Visa types</span>
          <span class="lsb-val">K-1 &amp; CR-1 / IR-1</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lsb-item">
          <span class="lsb-label">Required?</span>
          <span class="lsb-val">Not required — but helps</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lsb-item">
          <span class="lsb-label">Who writes it</span>
          <span class="lsb-val">Couple + witnesses</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lsb-item">
          <span class="lsb-label">Ideal length</span>
          <span class="lsb-val">1–2 pages each</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main content -->
  <div class="container">
    <div class="content-sidebar-grid">

      <!-- MAIN COLUMN -->
      <main class="main-col">

        <!-- What is it -->
        <section id="what-is-it" class="content-section">
          <h2>What Is a Bona Fide Marriage Letter?</h2>
          <p>A bona fide marriage letter — sometimes called a personal relationship statement or cover letter — is a written narrative explaining your relationship to a USCIS officer or consular officer. It tells your story: how you met, how the relationship developed, what your life together looks like, and why you intend to build a future together.</p>
          <p>There are two distinct types, and most strong applications include both:</p>

          <div class="letter-types-grid">
            <div class="letter-type-card">
              <div class="lt-icon">👫</div>
              <h3>The Couple's Own Statement</h3>
              <p>Written by the petitioner, the beneficiary, or both together. This is your first-person account of the relationship — the timeline, the visits, the day-to-day life, and your future plans. It provides narrative that photos and call logs alone cannot.</p>
              <div class="lt-tag">Most important</div>
            </div>
            <div class="letter-type-card">
              <div class="lt-icon">👥</div>
              <h3>Third-Party Witness Letters</h3>
              <p>Written by friends, family members, or colleagues who have personally observed the relationship. These corroborate your story from an outside perspective and carry significant weight when the author clearly knows the couple well.</p>
              <div class="lt-tag lt-tag-secondary">Strongly recommended</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The letter isn't a replacement for hard evidence — photos, communication logs, and travel records remain your foundation. But it gives the officer a human narrative to anchor all that evidence around, and it lets you address any unusual aspects of your relationship proactively rather than waiting for an RFE or interview question.</p>

          <div class="alert-box alert-amber">
            <div class="alert-icon">💡</div>
            <div>
              <strong>When to submit it</strong>
              <p>Include personal statements with your initial I-129F or DS-260 package. For adjustment of status (I-485), include both the couple's statement and 2–3 witness letters. If you receive a Request for Evidence (RFE), a detailed personal statement is often the most persuasive thing you can add.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Required vs Optional table -->
        <section id="required-optional" class="content-section">
          <h2>When Is It Required vs. Optional?</h2>
          <p>No immigration form specifically requires a personal narrative letter — but that doesn't mean it's unimportant. Here's how officers treat it at each stage:</p>

          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table class="info-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Application Type</th>
                  <th>Couple's Statement</th>
                  <th>Witness Letters</th>
                  <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>K-1 Fiancé Visa</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-recommended">Recommended</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-recommended">Recommended</span></td>
                  <td>Especially useful for online-only/LDR couples with fewer in-person visits</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>CR-1 / IR-1 Spousal Visa</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-recommended">Recommended</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-recommended">Recommended</span></td>
                  <td>Submitted with I-130; officers look for detailed relationship history</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Adjustment of Status (I-485)</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-required">Strongly recommended</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-required">Strongly recommended</span></td>
                  <td>Marriage interview typically involves detailed relationship questions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>RFE Response</strong></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-required">Often essential</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-required">Often essential</span></td>
                  <td>If officer questions relationship authenticity, a strong statement is critical</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- What to include — couple's statement -->
        <section id="couple-statement" class="content-section">
          <h2>What to Include in Your Own Letter (Couple's Statement)</h2>
          <p>Your personal statement should walk the officer through your relationship chronologically and specifically. Every claim you make should be verifiable by the evidence in your package. Here is what to cover:</p>

          <div class="include-list">

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">01</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>How You Met</h3>
                <p>Name the platform or setting specifically (e.g., "We met on Hinge on March 14, 2023" or "We were introduced by my cousin at a family gathering in Monterrey in July 2022"). Include the date, the context, and what prompted you to start talking. Officers want specificity — "we met online" by itself signals a generic template.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">02</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>How the Relationship Developed</h3>
                <p>Describe the progression: the first message, the first video call, how conversations moved from casual to personal. Mention approximately when you realized this was more than a casual connection. Include the platform you used for video calls (WhatsApp, FaceTime, Google Meet) and how often you were talking within the first few months.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">03</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>Your Visits Together</h3>
                <p>List each in-person visit with specific dates, cities, and at least a few activities or experiences you shared. Don't just say "we visited in 2023" — say "In September 2023, [Name] flew to Lisbon. We spent 12 days together — we cooked dinner at home most nights, visited Sintra, and met [Name]'s parents for the first time." Timestamps and locations are directly corroborated by passport stamps and photos in your packet.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">04</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>How You Communicate Day-to-Day</h3>
                <p>Describe your current communication routine: the apps you use, the typical frequency, and the nature of your conversations. Mention time zone differences if applicable — this is especially relevant for LDR couples and shows officers that you maintain the relationship across real logistical challenges. For example: "We video call every morning before [Name] leaves for work — it's evening for me in Brazil. We also text throughout the day on WhatsApp and share voice messages when we can't call."</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">05</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>Future Plans</h3>
                <p>Be specific and concrete: where you plan to live after the visa is approved, any wedding date or venue you've discussed, how you plan to handle the transition (employment, housing, family), and whether you've discussed children or other long-term goals. Officers are looking for evidence that this is a forward-looking, practical commitment — not just a romantic idea.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="include-item">
              <div class="include-num">06</div>
              <div class="include-body">
                <h3>Why This Person Specifically</h3>
                <p>This is the part most applicants skip, and it matters. Briefly explain — in personal, genuine terms — what qualities in your partner made you certain about this relationship. This doesn't need to be lengthy or poetic, but it should feel authentic and specific to your partner, not something you could say about anyone.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Third-party witness letters -->
        <section id="witness-letters" class="content-section">
          <h2>What to Include in a Third-Party Support Letter (Witnesses)</h2>
          <p>A witness letter is most valuable when the author clearly knows the couple well and can speak from direct personal observation — not just hearsay. Ideal witnesses include: a close friend who has met both of you, a family member who has visited or spoken with your partner, or someone who has observed the relationship develop over time (in person or via video calls).</p>

          <div class="witness-list">
            <div class="witness-item">
              <span class="witness-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Who the witness is and how they know the couple</strong>
                <p>Name, relationship to you, and how long they've known you. Officers need context to evaluate the letter's credibility.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="witness-item">
              <span class="witness-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Specific observations of the relationship</strong>
                <p>Describe a specific moment, conversation, or visit they witnessed — not just a general statement that "they seem happy together." For example: "I was there when [Name] flew in for Christmas 2023. I watched them interact for two weeks and it was clear they already had the kind of communication and rhythm of a long-established couple."</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="witness-item">
              <span class="witness-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Evidence of ongoing contact with the partner</strong>
                <p>If the witness has spoken to the foreign partner on video calls, met them in person, or exchanged messages, mention it — this shows the relationship exists in the witness's real world, not just on paper.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="witness-item">
              <span class="witness-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Confirmation of the genuine nature of the relationship</strong>
                <p>A sentence stating the witness believes the relationship is genuine and not entered into for immigration purposes. This doesn't need to be legalistic — just honest and direct.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="witness-item">
              <span class="witness-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Signature, printed name, date, and contact information</strong>
                <p>The letter should be signed and include the witness's full name and date. Some applicants include the witness's phone number or email in case the officer wants to verify.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- What NOT to include -->
        <section id="what-to-avoid" class="content-section">
          <h2>What NOT to Include — Red Flags That Raise Suspicion</h2>
          <p>Officers who review these letters daily know exactly what genuine ones look like — and what copy-paste ones look like. Avoid the following:</p>

          <div class="red-flags-grid">
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Vague, generic phrases</strong>
                <p>"We fell deeply in love." "Our connection was instant." "We knew we were meant to be together." These mean nothing without specifics to back them up. Every claim should be anchored to a real date, place, or event.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Copy-paste template language</strong>
                <p>Officers recognize boilerplate immediately. If your letter sounds like it was written by someone who has never met either of you, it undermines your entire evidence package. Personalize every sentence.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Future tense only — no relationship history</strong>
                <p>A letter that only describes what you plan to do together in the future, without describing how the relationship developed, suggests there is little shared history to write about. Officers want to see a real past.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>No specific dates, places, or names</strong>
                <p>If you can't remember when your first visit was, what city your partner lives in, or the names of their family members you've met — that's a red flag. Real couples know these details. Include them.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Inconsistencies with the rest of your package</strong>
                <p>If your letter says you first met in October 2022 but your passport stamp shows your first visit was in March 2023, an officer will notice. Review your letter against every document in your package before submitting.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">🚩</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Overly formal or legal-sounding language</strong>
                <p>Personal statements should sound like they were written by a person who is in love — not by an attorney. Write in plain, honest language. Officers find robotic legalese suspicious because real couples don't write that way.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Full sample letter template -->
        <section id="sample-letter" class="content-section">
          <h2>Full Sample Letter Template — Couple's Statement</h2>
          <p>The template below is a realistic example of what a strong couple's statement looks like. Replace every bracketed placeholder with your own specific information. The goal is that every sentence should only be true for the two of you.</p>

          <div class="letter-template">
            <div class="template-header">
              <span class="template-label">Sample Template — Couple's Personal Statement</span>
              <span class="template-note">~400 words · Replace all [bracketed] text with your own details</span>
            </div>
            <div class="template-body">
              <p class="letter-line">[City, State / Country]<br/>[Date]</p>

              <p class="letter-line">To Whom It May Concern,</p>

              <p class="letter-line">My name is [Your Full Name], a U.S. citizen residing in [City, State]. I am writing this statement in support of my fiancé(e) / spouse, [Partner's Full Name], and our petition for a [K-1 / CR-1] visa. I want to describe our relationship in my own words so that you have full context beyond the documents we have submitted.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">We first connected on [Platform — e.g., Hinge / OkCupid / Instagram] on [Month Year]. [Partner's Name] sent me a message about [specific detail — a photo, a prompt answer, a shared interest]. Within a week we had moved to WhatsApp and were talking for hours most evenings. By [Month, approximately 6–8 weeks later], we were video calling daily — [Partner's Name] in [their city] and me in [your city], navigating a [X]-hour time difference that we have managed every day since.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">I flew to [Partner's Country / City] for the first time in [Month Year]. We spent [X] days together. I still remember the moment I saw [him/her/them] at the arrivals hall at [Airport Name] — everything that had felt real over video finally felt tangible. We spent that first trip [specific activities — e.g., hiking in the mountains north of the city, cooking dinner at [Partner's Name]'s apartment, meeting [his/her/their] mother and sister for the first time at a Sunday lunch]. Those [X] days erased whatever doubts the distance had created.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">We have since visited each other [X] more times — [brief list: e.g., "[Partner's Name] came to [Your City] in March 2024 for three weeks; I returned to [their city] in August 2024 for our engagement trip"]. Between visits, we video call every [morning/evening] and text throughout the day. We watch films together over [Netflix Party / Teleparty], have played [game] online, and send voice messages during the hours the time difference makes calls difficult.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">I proposed to [Partner's Name] on [Date] at [Location / description of the moment]. [He/She/They] said yes. We have already [describe concrete planning: chosen a wedding venue / set a date of [Month Year] / told both families / started apartment searching in [City]].</p>

              <p class="letter-line">I want to be clear about why I want to marry [Partner's Name] specifically: [2–3 specific, genuine sentences about your partner's character, values, or the way they show up in your life — this is the part no template can write for you].</p>

              <p class="letter-line">Our relationship is genuine, loving, and forward-facing. I respectfully ask that this statement be considered alongside the supporting documents we have submitted.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">Sincerely,</p>
              <p class="letter-line">[Signature]<br/>[Your Full Printed Name]<br/>[Date]</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Sample witness letter -->
        <section id="sample-witness" class="content-section">
          <h2>Sample Third-Party Witness Letter Template</h2>
          <p>Below is an example of what a friend's support letter should look like. Note the specificity — the witness is not just saying "they seem happy" but describing a real moment they observed.</p>

          <div class="letter-template letter-template-witness">
            <div class="template-header">
              <span class="template-label">Sample Template — Friend / Family Witness Letter</span>
              <span class="template-note">~200 words · Written by a third party who knows the couple</span>
            </div>
            <div class="template-body">
              <p class="letter-line">[City, State / Country]<br/>[Date]</p>

              <p class="letter-line">To Whom It May Concern,</p>

              <p class="letter-line">My name is [Witness Full Name]. I am a [friend / cousin / colleague] of [Petitioner's Name] and have known [him/her/them] for [X] years. I am writing to confirm the genuine nature of [his/her/their] relationship with [Partner's Name].</p>

              <p class="letter-line">I first heard about [Partner's Name] in [Month Year], when [Petitioner's Name] mentioned [him/her/them] frequently over dinner. I met [Partner's Name] for the first time in [Month Year] when [he/she/they] visited [City] — we all went [brief specific activity together]. I was struck by how natural and easy their dynamic was; there was clearly a strong foundation of communication and genuine affection built over [time period].</p>

              <p class="letter-line">Since then, I have spoken with [Partner's Name] several times over video call and witnessed how [Petitioner's Name] has approached this relationship: with patience, commitment, and a clear sense of shared purpose. I have no doubt that their relationship is authentic and that both parties sincerely intend to build a life together.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">I am happy to be contacted if additional information is needed.</p>

              <p class="letter-line">Sincerely,</p>
              <p class="letter-line">[Signature]<br/>[Full Printed Name]<br/>[Date]<br/>[Phone / Email — optional]</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- LDR tips -->
        <section id="ldr-tips" class="content-section">
          <h2>Tips for Long-Distance Couples</h2>
          <p>LDR couples face a unique challenge: you have a rich relationship, but much of it happened over a screen. Here's how to communicate that effectively in your letter:</p>

          <div class="tips-list">
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">01</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Acknowledge the distance honestly — then explain how you managed it</h3>
                <p>Officers reviewing LDR applications know the distance is real. Don't pretend it's been easy. Instead, describe specifically how you maintained the relationship despite it: the daily video calls, the time zone adjustments, the planning that went into each visit. Honesty about the challenge makes your commitment more credible, not less.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">02</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Describe the time zone specifically</h3>
                <p>Mention the exact time difference and how it affects your communication routine. "We have a 9-hour difference — [Partner] is in [Country] and I'm on the East Coast. We call every evening my time, which is already morning for [him/her/them]." This level of detail is something only a real couple would know.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">03</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Reference shared online experiences</h3>
                <p>Real LDR couples build shared experiences online. Mention the specific shows you've watched together, the games you've played, the routines you've developed. "Every Sunday we cook the same recipe at the same time over video call" is memorable, specific, and human.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">04</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Be specific about the immigration plan</h3>
                <p>Officers want to see that you've thought through the practical steps. Don't just say you want to be together — say where you'll live, how you'll handle the job transition, whether you've already secured housing, and what your timeline looks like after the visa is approved. This signals a real plan, not a vague intention.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">05</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Tie your letter to your evidence</h3>
                <p>Reference what's in your evidence package without repeating it verbatim. For example: "We have submitted call logs from WhatsApp showing daily contact over 18 months" or "The photos from our September 2023 trip to Lisbon are included in our packet as Exhibit C." This creates a coherent package where the letter and evidence reinforce each other.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Checklist -->
        <section id="checklist" class="content-section">
          <h2>Checklist Before Submitting Your Letter</h2>
          <p>Run through this before including your letter in any immigration package:</p>

          <div class="submit-checklist">
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Length is 1–2 pages</strong>
                <p>Couple's statement should be 400–600 words. Witness letters should be around 200–300 words. Longer is not better — focus on quality and specificity.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Every claim includes a specific date, place, or name</strong>
                <p>Go through the letter and flag any sentence that could apply to any couple. Replace it with something that could only be true for you.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Consistent with all other documents</strong>
                <p>Cross-check every date, city, and timeline in your letter against your passport stamps, photo metadata, call logs, and forms. Any inconsistency becomes an officer's question.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Signed and dated by the author</strong>
                <p>Both the couple's statement and each witness letter must be signed by the person who wrote it, with their printed name and the date of signature.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Translated if not in English</strong>
                <p>Any letter not written in English must include a certified English translation. The translator must include a certification statement with their name and a statement of competency.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Witness letters are from people who actually know you</strong>
                <p>A letter from someone who has only heard about your relationship second-hand carries little weight. Prioritize witnesses who have met your partner in person or via video call, or who have directly observed the relationship develop.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Free of copy-paste template language</strong>
                <p>Read the letter out loud. If any sentence sounds like something you'd find in a generic example online, rewrite it in your own words with your specific details.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="sc-item">
              <span class="sc-check">✓</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Proofread by both partners</strong>
                <p>Both the petitioner and the beneficiary should read the couple's statement. Your stories must align — you will likely be asked about this relationship at interview, and inconsistencies between the letter and your interview answers are a serious red flag.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQs -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Is a bona fide marriage letter required for immigration?</summary>
              <p>It is not formally required — no USCIS form asks for a personal narrative. However, it is strongly recommended for K-1, CR-1, and IR-1 applications and is standard practice for adjustment of status. Officers welcome the context it provides, and for LDR couples with fewer in-person visits, a detailed personal statement can meaningfully strengthen your case.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How long should a bona fide marriage letter be?</summary>
              <p>One to two pages is the sweet spot for a couple's statement — roughly 400 to 600 words. Third-party witness letters should be shorter: one page or 200 to 300 words. Officers review hundreds of files; a focused, specific letter is far more persuasive than a lengthy, repetitive one.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Who should write the bona fide marriage letter?</summary>
              <p>There are two types. The couple's own statement is written by the petitioner, the beneficiary, or both. Third-party support letters are written by friends, family members, or colleagues who have personally observed the relationship — either in person or through ongoing contact. Aim for 2 to 3 witness letters from people who know the couple well.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Does a bona fide marriage letter need to be notarized?</summary>
              <p>Generally no. USCIS does not require notarization for personal relationship statements. More important than notarization is that the letter is signed, dated, specific, and consistent with your other evidence. Some applicants choose to notarize witness letters to add credibility, but it is not a requirement.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What if English isn't my first language?</summary>
              <p>Any document submitted to USCIS or a U.S. consulate in a language other than English must include a certified English translation. The translator must certify their competency in both languages and confirm the translation is complete and accurate. You may include both the original and the translation — this is often encouraged.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can I use a template for my bona fide marriage letter?</summary>
              <p>You can use a template as a structural guide, but you must replace every detail with your own real information. Officers are experienced at identifying boilerplate language, and a clearly generic letter can actually raise suspicion. The sample on this page is designed to show you the right structure and level of specificity — use it as a scaffold, not a script.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

